{"type":"message","id":"85e3055d","parentId":"1c6e7a31","timestamp":"2026-02-19T18:52:55.493Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Implementing the Circuit Breaker**\n\nI'm now focused on the implementation details for the `@circuit_breaker` decorator, specifically within `src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py`. The core logic is shaping up: latency thresholds, call count tracking, and the state transitions (OPEN, CLOSED) tied to trade suspension are all in place. I'm currently wrestling with the 60-second reset timer and how best to integrate that with the decorator.\n\n\n**Refactoring Circuit Breaker Logic**\n\nI've decided to abandon the `circuitbreaker` library and instead craft a custom solution within `src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py`. The focus is on implementing the specific failure criteria - three calls exceeding 500ms latency triggers the OPEN state. I'm structuring this as a class for clarity, with methods for state transitions and the timer reset. The `call_with_circuit_breaker` interface will be maintained through a wrapper function.\n\n\n**Constructing the Core Components**\n\nI'm now deep in the implementation. I've defined the `CircuitBreaker` class, managing the state, failure counts, and the reset timer. `allow_request` dictates request flow based on the circuit's state, and `record_success`/`record_failure` methods handle state transitions. I'm focusing on ensuring all the states work as expected, including half-open state testing after the timer expires.\n\n\n**Rewriting the Circuit Breaker**\n\nI've just finished the complete rewrite of `src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py`, swapping out the complex wrapper for a simpler, custom class to manage the state transitions.  The code is now focused on the exact requirements. The `call_with_circuit_breaker` interface is retained through a wrapper. I will also be looking over `src/dmarket/api/client.py` shortly to verify the wrapper usage.\n\n\n**Rebuilding with a Fresh Start**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in rewriting `src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py`. The goal is to provide a decorator (`@circuit_breaker`) and the `call_with_circuit_breaker` interface, aligning with the project's architecture. The new code leverages a `CircuitBreaker` class for state management. I am also making sure to properly handle the exceptions and latency, as defined by the user. I'll test the integration of this new code soon.\n\n\n**Crafting the Implementation**\n\nI'm currently focused on the implementation of the new `src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py`. I've rewritten it to meet the given specifications. I've retained `call_with_circuit_breaker` for compatibility, and I've also implemented the `@circuit_breaker` decorator. The code now uses a `CircuitBreaker` class to manage state, with methods for recording successes, failures, and handling the reset timer. I have also added `EndpointType` to maintain compatibility with other existing code.\n\n\n**Refining Implementation Strategy**\n\nI'm currently crafting the `src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py` file, building upon the requirements.  The design includes the `@circuit_breaker` decorator and the `call_with_circuit_breaker` function.  I've added the `EndpointType` enum for compatibility.  I am also verifying that the client imports function as expected. I'm focusing on simplicity and alignment with the initial specifications, including the critical latency checks and state transitions.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771527175492_67","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"import time\nimport asyncio\nimport functools\nimport logging\nfrom enum import StrEnum\nfrom typing import Any, Callable, Awaitable, TypeVar\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n# Constants from requirements\nLATENCY_THRESHOLD_MS = 500\nFAILURE_THRESHOLD = 3\nRESET_TIMEOUT_S = 60\n\nclass EndpointType(StrEnum):\n    \"\"\"Types of API endpoints (kept for compatibility).\"\"\"\n    MARKET = \"market\"\n    TARGETS = \"targets\"\n    BALANCE = \"balance\"\n    INVENTORY = \"inventory\"\n    TRADING = \"trading\"\n\nclass CircuitBreakerState:\n    CLOSED = \"CLOSED\"\n    OPEN = \"OPEN\"\n    HALF_OPEN = \"HALF_OPEN\"\n\nclass CircuitBreaker:\n    def __init__(self, name: str = \"default\"):\n        self.name = name\n        self.state = CircuitBreakerState.CLOSED\n        self.failure_count = 0\n        self.last_failure_time = 0\n        self.reset_timeout = RESET_TIMEOUT_S\n\n    def allow_request(self) -> bool:\n        if self.state == CircuitBreakerState.OPEN:\n            if time.time() - self.last_failure_time > self.reset_timeout:\n                self.state = CircuitBreakerState.HALF_OPEN\n                logger.info(f\"Circuit breaker '{self.name}' entered HALF_OPEN state\")\n                return True\n            return False\n        return True\n\n    def record_success(self):\n        if self.state == CircuitBreakerState.HALF_OPEN:\n            self.state = CircuitBreakerState.CLOSED\n            self.failure_count = 0\n            logger.info(f\"Circuit breaker '{self.name}' closed (recovered)\")\n        elif self.state == CircuitBreakerState.CLOSED:\n            # Reset failure count on success in CLOSED state if we want strict consecutive failures\n            # But the prompt says \"If latency > 500ms for 3 calls\", usually implying consecutive or within a window.\n            # I'll implement consecutive for simplicity and strictness.\n            self.failure_count = 0\n\n    def record_failure(self):\n        self.failure_count += 1\n        logger.warning(f\"Circuit breaker '{self.name}' recorded failure/latency ({self.failure_count}/{FAILURE_THRESHOLD})\")\n        if self.failure_count >= FAILURE_THRESHOLD:\n            self.state = CircuitBreakerState.OPEN\n            self.last_failure_time = time.time()\n            logger.error(f\"Circuit breaker '{self.name}' opened! Stopping trading.\")\n\n    async def call(self, func: Callable[..., Awaitable[Any]], *args, **kwargs) -> Any:\n        if not self.allow_request():\n            logger.warning(f\"Circuit breaker '{self.name}' is OPEN. Request blocked.\")\n            # We can raise a specific exception or return None\n            raise Exception(f\"Circuit Breaker '{self.name}' is OPEN\")\n\n        start_time = time.perf_counter()\n        try:\n            result = await func(*args, **kwargs)\n            latency = (time.perf_counter() - start_time) * 1000\n            \n            if latency > LATENCY_THRESHOLD_MS:\n                logger.warning(f\"High latency detected: {latency:.2f}ms > {LATENCY_THRESHOLD_MS}ms\")\n                self.record_failure()\n            else:\n                self.record_success()\n                \n            return result\n        except Exception as e:\n            # Check if it's the circuit breaker exception itself to avoid double counting (unlikely here)\n            if str(e).startswith(\"Circuit Breaker\"):\n                raise e\n                \n            logger.error(f\"Call failed with exception: {e}\")\n            # Count exceptions as failures too, or strictly latency?\n            # \"If latency > 500ms for 3 calls\".\n            # Usually exceptions (timeouts, 500s) are also failures.\n            self.record_failure()\n            raise e\n\n# Global instance\n_circuit_breaker = CircuitBreaker(\"dmarket_api\")\n\ndef circuit_breaker(func):\n    \"\"\"Decorator for circuit breaker logic.\"\"\"\n    @functools.wraps(func)\n    async def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n        return await _circuit_breaker.call(func, *args, **kwargs)\n    return wrapper\n\nasync def call_with_circuit_breaker(\n    func: Callable[..., Awaitable[Any]], \n    *args, \n    **kwargs\n) -> Any:\n    \"\"\"Wrapper for backward compatibility.\"\"\"\n    # Remove arguments that are not part of the target function signature\n    # but were used in the old circuit breaker implementation\n    kwargs.pop('endpoint_type', None)\n    kwargs.pop('fallback', None)\n    \n    return await _circuit_breaker.call(func, *args, **kwargs)\n","file_path":"src/utils/api_circuit_breaker.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":19581,"output":2726,"cacheRead":16790,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":22307,"cost":{"input":0.039161999999999995,"output":0.032712,"cacheRead":0.0033580000000000003,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.075232}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771527148730}}
